<span class='blue strong'>The situation in Luyten<$slashspan>

This is a high-level status update to all GTA and PVN personnel in Luyten. I would like to extend my thanks to Lieutenant Commander Petoph and Lieutenant Dedwen of the PVN for their assistance in preparing the translation.

First, the bad news. We have been unable to break through the raider blockade in Laramis. We've lost contact with every probe we've sent through the node, and the raiders responded to our most recent attempt with a retaliatory strike against civilian habitats. We have likewise been unable to restore the Laramis comm relay to proper working order. For now, we must assume we're on our own.

We've also spotted raider forces near the Barnard's Star and Wolf 359 nodes. Since these systems don't lead us any closer to GTA space, we've decided not to risk exploring them further.

On a more positive note, we've successfully evacuated over 60% of Luyten's civilian population to secure locations scattered across the system. The LNA's Barracudas CEU squadron has deployed subspace decoy beacons to obscure their exact positions. Our cruisers have been jumping around the system at random to further mislead hostile <span class='blue'>SUTRAC<$slashspan>. The decoys seem to be working so far, so we'll keep up the pretense as long as necessary.

The majority of pending evacuations are in the system's Oort Cloud. Evacuating this region is tricky due to both the inherent difficulty of subspace navigation so far up the gravity well and the sheer number of small mining facilities. On the other hand, these same factors also make it equally difficult to attack.

We expect to complete 85% of civilian evacuations by the end of the month."
