6747, "(fr)The Second Dawn Society has been a long-standing enigma of Luyten. Now they're missing, and the LNA wants to know why."
6748, "(fr)!html <div class='blue'>Wayfarer Station<br$slash>Luyten System<br$slash>2342/05/06<$slashdiv>

<span class='blue'>Emergency update<$slashspan>

Four hours ago, at 1445 station time, <span class='red'>Captain Jan Varner<$slashspan> was found to be in contact with elements of the raider leadership. The specific nature of their conversation indicated a pre-existing connection which the <span class='red'>captain<$slashspan> had failed to properly disclose. Since he has so far refused to invoke <span class='blue'>General Order Four<$slashspan>, a conference of this task force's leadership has concluded he is not simply following classified orders. As such, by the decision of the same conference, <span class='red'>Captain Varner<$slashspan> has been removed from command. I should emphasize that we have neither the information nor the authority for a proper court-martial at this time. Nevertheless, we do believe there is sufficient doubt as to his intentions to justify his removal.

I've never been one for speeches. I know this must come as something of a shock, but we still have a job to do. We can't let this shakeup in our leadership set us back, and that's all the time I'll spend on it. We'll continue to maintain fighter patrols, and I've appointed Captain Rostami, formerly of the GTC Eudora, to my old liaison role. Flight crews, you'll receive your briefings from him from now on. Likewise, he'll keep you informed as to any change in our understanding of the raiders or <span class='red'>Captain Varner's<$slashspan> involvement with them. In the mean time, keep your minds our known enemies in this system. I've asked our liaison office to the LNA to put together an official release. Until it goes out, keep the chatter about this to a minimum.

Life must go on, and so do our responsibilities in this system. Since you're all already here, I'm turning the mic over to Captain Rostami to introduce some new equipment. Captain?"
6749, "(fr)!html <span class='blue'>New technology: GTM MX-64 Roc<$slashspan>

Thank you, Captain Jers.

In light of recent developments, STX Exploration has made the first production run of their new MX-64 heat-seeking missile available to us ahead of schedule. Like its predecessor the MX-50, the Roc passively acquires targets, with no need for an active aspect lock. With high marks for hull damage and cycle time, the MX-64 is particularly suited to snap shots at light raider craft. With a maximum range of just under two kilometers, the missile is also suitable for sniping hostile turrets, subsystems, and sentry guns.

As a heat-seeker, the Roc is easily mislead by countermeasures. Initial tests indicate that the weapon is best fired from directly fore or aft of enemy fighters. Pilots in a space superiority role may consider pairing a bank of Rocs with a second bank of Sirens for maximum tactical versatility."
6750, "(fr)!html <span class='blue'>New technology: DIRCM BriteBurst<$slashspan>

Calling this $quotenew$quote is a bit of a stretch, but it's new to us as a unit. The BriteBurst is an old countermeasure, typically carried by private security forces. During their time with us, the Opportunity's security detail has discovered they're unusually effective at misleading the raiders' long-range shield-breaker missiles. Elias Pendergast has made a number of the flares available to us, and Amanu Station is making preparations to assemble more as needed. If you choose to carry the BriteBurst, you'll want to launch them earlier than you're used to for maximum effect.

That is all, pilots. I'll see you soon for your frag briefings."
6751, "(fr)!html Alright, pilots, listen up. Today's mission concerns one of Luyten's more esoteric factions, so pay close attention. According to our contacts in the Luyten New Alliance, the Second Dawn Society operates out of Megiddo Station in the system's Oort Cloud, under the direction of one Amira Ekul, an old-money blueblood from Delta Serpentis who gave up considerable privilege and prestige to come here. The SDS sees itself as a failsafe against a possible second Shivan Incursion, and is devoted to survival above all else. Rumors persist of former GTI personnel among their ranks who defected to avoid persecution after the Hades Rebellion, along with more ordinary criminal elements."
6752, "(fr)Oort Cloud"
6753, "(fr)!html While the SDS intends to create a fully self-sustaining society, they currently maintain limited trade with the LNA for specialized materials they don't yet have the ability to fabricate. In exchange, they provide a police presence at the outside of the system. Several mining groups owe their lives to the timely intervention of SDS pilots. Recovered footage indicates they operate a mixture of <span class='white'>early Great War-era fighters<$slashspan>, as well as custom-designed craft built in their own workshops. Given the organization's secretive nature, little is known about these classes. The <span class='blue'>Society<$slashspan> is also partial to <span class='white'>booby traps<$slashspan> at key locations. In general, they should be regarded as a small, but well-equipped and highly competent system militia."
6754, "(fr)SDS fighter corps"
6755, "(fr)Unique ships"
6756, "Mines"
6757, "Sentinelles"
6758, "(fr)EWAR"
6759, "(fr)!html Believing that too much contact with the outside world would compromise their self-sufficiency, the SDS conducts its trade meetings at a small depot just outside the Oort Cloud, overseen by a Tyrving weapons platform. This is one of many <span class='white'>booby traps<$slashspan> the SDS maintains as part of their anti-Shivan survivalist ethos, which double as safe havens for civilian ships in the <span class='yellow'>Cloud<$slashspan>.

To prevent the location of their headquarters being revealed, their trade delegations make a point of remaining in the area until all possible observers have departed. Neither the GTA, the LNA, nor STX Exploration can say with any certainty where the SDS headquarters is located. <span class='white'>This just became a problem.<$slashspan>"
6760, "(fr)Exchange depot"
6761, "(fr)LNA trade"
6762, "Pilleurs ?"
6763, "(fr)SDS trade"
6764, "(fr)!html Seven days ago, LNA executives offered <span class='blue'>Society<$slashspan> representatives technical data on <span class='white'>genetic resequencing equipment<$slashspan> in exchange for greater cooperation against the raiders. The SDS accepted the offer, but failed to make the rendezvous. Probes dispatched to the exchange platform haven't reported back, nor have long-range scans of the area turned up any signs of them.

LNA Command fears the raiders may have located and destroyed Megiddo Station. If this is the case, it represents not only the loss of a valuable ally, but a marked uptick in the raiders' capabilities as well. We have agreed to a joint operation to figure out what happened."
6765, "(fr)!html Dr. Tsega Sarno, who has had positive contact with the SDS before, has volunteered the LNAe Lavoisier and its sensor suite for this operation. I understand you flew escort for her in the Laramis op, so I won't waste time on introductions. You'll join two LNA fighters, designated Xi 1 and Xi 2, as escort. Alpha 1 will have tactical authority over both wings, but we'll be relying on Sarno and the Lavoisier to tell us where to look. You should expect to be out of contact with Wayfarer Station for the duration of this mission. Given its significance, Sublieutenant Kinson's support ship will deploy along with you."
6766, "(fr)SDS"
6767, "(fr)Tiger"
6768, "(fr)Socrates"
6769, "(fr)Second Dawn Society"
6770, "(fr)!html The doctor wants to start with a sensor sweep of the exchange site. Perhaps the Lavoisier's sensors can detect residual subspace activity - exactly the sort of thing the SDS hoped to avoid in the first place - or learn something from the depot's computer systems. Jumps so far up the gravity well are difficult to calculate, so you'll rendezvous with her a safe distance from the depot and proceed via sublight drives. How we proceed after that point will depend on what you find at the depot."
6771, "(fr)!html Pilots, we're heading into an unknown situation with ambiguous objectives and an unknown number of hostiles. <span class='white'>Stay alert.<$slashspan> You may encounter raider forces, or any <span class='white'>booby traps<$slashspan> the raiders have managed to avoid triggering. Choose your loadout carefully. We don't know what we're up against, so consider bringing a mix of anti-hull and anti-shield weaponry. The new Roc missiles will let you sweep static defenses at a safe range.

Get in, keep your wits about you, and figure out what happened to those people. If there are any survivors, bring them home. The Lavoisier will jump to the op site in one hour, so be ready by then. Dismissed."
6772, "(fr)!html Welcome to Megiddo Station, Alliance pilots. My name is Amira Ekul. This is Sunghwan Ko, commander of our fighter corps, Iskandar Elnu of station security, and this little bundle of joy is <span class='blue'>Amira Jr<$slashspan>. Patrols are sweeping the station for any militants in hiding, and the HoL officers who surrendered during the engagement are being loaded onto transports bound for Wayfarer Station. To make a long story short? We won.

I'm sure you have questions, so I'll fill you in as best I can. Six days ago, one of our patrols picked up a distress call from the <span class='green italic'>PVC Pa-Bef<$slashspan> near the Laramis node. That's a little bit out of our normal range, but orbital patterns worked in our favor. If the Imperium had sent a ship to check up the situation here, we weren't about to let the raiders get their grubby little hands on it. Of course, when the patrol got there, there wasn't much they could do but call in a salvage team. We were going to turn it over at our next meeting with the LNA, but...

Well, it was a trap. Holly had sent the distress call, and when the <span class='red italic'>Pa-Bef<$slashspan> got in range of Megiddo, her navigation system painted us for a pair of Newets and the <span class='red italic'>Hedjhotep<$slashspan>. Speaking frankly, they caught us with our pants down. We let the raiders take up too much of our attention and simply weren't ready for a cruiser strike. That's on me, and I'm not too proud to own up to it."
6773, "(fr)!html Now, that brings us to the traps you ran into. Those are a proof of concept - a demonstration of how we might mislead a Shivan< force, if and when they return. They're supposed to be dormant, but Holly forced us to bring them online. Fortunately, they didn't know about the Larawag fighters, and we weren't about to tell them. They've got some sort of old GTI tech on board for remote operation. In theory, they'd back up the missile probes. In practice? Larawag's telemetry let Mr. Elnu coordinate a jailbreak with your arrival."
6774, "(fr)!html Fortunately, we made the right call. Holly didn't just want to kill us outright. They wanted our supplies, our ships and our workshops, to bolster their own fleet. They took prisoners to $quotesecure our cooperation$quote, and that's where they made their big mistake - holding the station's security forces on their own transport. We think they were counting on their space superiority to avoid resistance - and that's where you came in.

Now, if the cane didn't give it away, I'm not much of a warrior. But I'll have my own battles to fight in the coming days. There are people on this very station who will use this incident to delegitimize me, and I can only guess at the outcome of that political fight. But I can promise you this much, pilots. You've brought what could have been a very messy ordeal to a quick end with minimal casualties, and I'm not about to forget that.

We're stronger together. Today demonstrated that. My forces are now at your disposal."
6775, "(fr)!html Pilots, you were assigned to protect the Lavoisier. Its destruction represents not only the loss of a valuable strategic asset and the failure of our attempt to contact the Second Dawn Society, but also a significant sticking point in our relationship with the Luyten New Alliance. We're facing oppositions on two fronts - the raiders and their blockade of the system, and the Hammer of Light forces and their mysterious objectives. We need to build alliances, not hostility.

Nonetheless, there was no way you could have predicted the mortar trap. Why the LNA didn't think to provide more detailed information is uncertain, and I must take some responsibility for not pursuing it further. Unfortunately, with tension between us and them and the addition of a new unknown at the system's rim, things are only going to get harder."
6776, "(fr)Take out the mortar turrets ASAP. The platform carries six mortar turrets which will whittle down the Lavoisier, and is defended by four groups of three Cerberus-class sentry guns. Your best bet is to avoid the closest sentry group and snipe the platform's turrets with missiles - Rocs, Sirens, and Ballistae are all good choices for this. Try not to get too close or you'll take a lot of damage.

If the raider fighters give you trouble, call Xi wing for cover.

The checkpoint will rearm you even if you forgot to call support on the way over."
6777, "(fr)!html With the destruction of the SDS transport <span class='green italic'>Fujin<$slashspan> and its security personnel, Amira Ekul and their crew were unable to hold back the HoL militants on the Izanami. If there's any consolation to be had, it's that the SDS command staff chose to go down fighting rather than be taken prisoner. Unfortunately, this is cold comfort in light of the changing strategic picture."
6778, "(fr)The initial Thot launch isn't much of a threat to you, but will shred an unescorted Proton. Close with them as soon as they're on scope, and hit them with everything you can until they break formation. The faster you take out those ships, the less damage they can deal to the Fujin's hull, and the easier it'll be to escort the rest of the way. You'll have plenty of time to rearm, so don't be shy about using missiles.

The subsequent fighter wings will always be looking for an angle on the Fujin, so make sure to stick close to it. Your wingmates can help a lot here."
6779, "(fr)The SDS ship Izanami was destroyed with all hands by Hammer of Light strikecraft. Critical SDS personnel, including the organization's founder, were aboard and unable to escape. If there's any consolation to be had, it's that neither was the HoL capture team. Unfortunately, this is cold comfort in light of the changing strategic picture."
6780, "(fr)Whatever you do, don't be stuck in a dogfight while Taureau is closing in. If you notice yourself getting pulled away from the Fujin and Izanami, either disengage and return to them, or call your wingmates over to help you out. If you fight as a unit, you should take out Bélier and Cancer while Taureau is still far away, so take that opportunity to rearm.

Taureau is escorted by Scorpio (four Thots). Avoid engaging them until you've disrupted the bomber formation. If you have to engage Scorpio, do it with missiles, and don't get dragged into a dogfight. Pressing F10 will mark Scorpio on your HUD, so use that to plan your approach.

If you took Larawag 1, you'll have access to the Ballista and the Shield Breaker. This is a powerful combination against Taureau wing - a pair of Ballista missiles will take out an Osiris in one hit if you've broken its shields first. The S-Breaker's long range - 1600 meters - will help here. As a bomber, the Athena has thick shields itself, so don't worry too much about return fire from Scorpio or Taureau, especially if you divert energy away from guns.

Leave shooting down torpedoes to your wingmates. The more of them you can keep intact, the more wiggle room you'll have as you engage Taureau."
6781, "(fr)The events of today represent the complete dissolution of the Second Dawn Society as an organization. We came in expecting raiders, but the reality is much worse than we feared. Megiddo Station, its supplies, workshops, and repair facilities, remain in Hammer of Light control. Our one advantage over the Hammer in Luyten was the logistical support provided by our installations. Just like the capture of the PVD Frontière in Antarès, they've leveled the playing field in their favor.

Pilots, I want you to know that I don't hold any of you responsible. We are up against an audacious, cunning foe with a history of defying the odds. In spite of this outcome, you fought well out there. We'll all need to keep that up in the weeks to come. I'll be consulting with my LNA and Vasudan counterparts to plan our next moves. In the mean time, I'd like you all to schedule simulator rotations against Hammer forces."
6782, "(fr)We've been dealt a major blow today, pilots, and we'll all need to be at our best if we're going to recover from it. Dismissed."
