7583, "(fr)Morale on my end's taken a real nosedive recently. The AI is strategically sound, and we've completed final verification that it will know how to work with your manufacturing systems. We haven't been able to get the IFF working in a way that we can prove the Shivans won't be able to subvert. If we want to make the galaxy safe for whoever comes after us, we need that system working. (cont)"
7584, "(fr)If the Alliance can't stop the Shivans, that weapon will be our legacy. The IFF problem is concerning, but we always knew time was the enemy.

INEDAM can monitor the Shivans and build a fleet to fight them. That's good enough. I'm ordering it set to ready status.


---"
7585, "(fr)Ambrosia intended to pay for the station with the proceeds from their contract to operate the GTE CARTER. The Carter's subsequent crash, together with the Vostok objects' mineral wealth being less than expected, lead Ambrosia to abandon their designs in Luyten altogether, leaving the subject in an incomplete state.

Purpose: To provide a secure, low-visibility facility for the aspects of Project INEDAM which do not comply with 3CAWS. 

(Cont)"
7586, "(fr)Risks: As a former civilian installation, the subject is not unknown outside of GTI. It is, however, obscure, especially since the dissolution of Ambrosia's mining division, and overshadowed by the infamous Carter wreck. To mitigate this risk, we recommend employing cover story B-2, C-2, or C-5, although any standard cover story should be sufficient. (cont)"
7587, "(fr)Luyten's solar flares provide a risk to electronic systems and may prove especially problematic for an AI, although this risk is naturally mitigated by the asteroid material. Should the subject's habitation or administrative capabilities prove insufficient, Sites 26 and 58 are easily accessible by subspace and could be reactivated in an auxiliary capacity, although neither is sufficient for the project's research needs.

-
Attachments: [1$slash1, Farewell address by Ambrosia's CEO, transcript follows.]

"
7588, "(fr)Like the dwarves of Tolkein's Moria, we dug too greedily and too deep. The asteroids we identified in Luyten hold valuable material, yes, but in far lower quantities than expected. In our haste to get a foothold in the system, we set up a station on the word of a shaky, incomplete assay, and scant months later, it's run dry. Perhaps we could salvage the situation by turning it into a mining hub, were it not for my second great mistake. (cont)"
7589, "(fr)With the loss of the Carter, the Alliance has pulled our contract. Again, the fundamental problem was haste. Had we vetted the specifications more carefully, we would have identified the flaws that lead to its loss.

During my tenure as CEO, I've followed an aggressive, high-risk$slashhigh-reward strategy. I counted on my people to rise to the challenge. They did - until I gave them an impossible challenge, then another. 
"
7590, "(fr)I was too caught up in my own world to listen to my own experts telling me my timeline was too short, too aggressive. I take full responsibility for these recent disasters, and as such, I'm stepping down.
 --


Annalise Toqueville

CEO-Emeritus

Ambrosia Logistical Solutions"
