8553, "(fr)Duamutef"
8554, "(fr)!html We can't predict what specific position IN.E.D.A.M.01 will take up around the station, but its previous attacks have given us a general idea. We know it tends to come in close to bring its heavy gauss cannons to bear on the primary target, supplemented by bomber wings from its hangar. The Lovelace, Shen Kuo, and Shannon are monitoring subspace traffic around the station. Their sensor suites will give Captain Jers' units a few extra seconds to get into position, and once the battle starts, they'll give us advance warning of incoming reinforcements.

Tactical simulations project that our defenses will be sufficient to hold back the worst of IN.E.D.A.M.01's arsenal, and it will likely adjust tactics to sweep static defenses. <span class='white'>The flak and artillery platforms are expendable,<$slashspan> but protect them if you can. The more we can force the attacking forces to split up, the easier time we'll have executing our own plan."
8555, "(fr)!html Our counterattack consists of three phases. In the first phase, the GTA's 508th will prosecute IN.E.D.A.M.01's main turrets. We need those guns destroyed to preserve the station's hull integrity, but we also hope to force the carrier to call in for reinforcements. Ker-Ahes drone controllers don't have any weapons of their own, and Morgens gunships have relatively light armor, so INEDAM will have to pull back some of its drones to cover their arrival, leaving it off-balance. That's the cue for the second phase of our plan.

Alpha wing, you're in charge of space superiority during this phase of the operation. Bêta wing has primary responsibility for the anti-turret action. Continue your attack until INEDAM calls in for reinforcements. In the unlikely event that it fails to do so, Captain Jers will lead a cruiser strike against the carrier, at which point you'll be called back to provide it with fighter cover."
8556, "(fr)!html The LNA's&nbsp$semicolonXi and Chi wings will provide fighter cover for the station and our warships. Their main job is to deny space superiority to the enemy. The INEDAM carrier will deploy overwhelming numbers, and keeping them under control will be crucial to our defense. Additionally, the PVN has transferred four Tauret heavy fighters to our hangar, which are being prepped for launch now. They'll use the callsign Rho and carry Ballista missiles for long-ranged bomber suppression. Alpha 1, coordinate with this unit as you see fit.

We'll be facing down enormous numbers, so we need our hangar intact. We're deploying our Hammer of Light assets around the bay to intercept anything that gets too close. They'll also provide an additional layer of torpedo interception.

Nardi wing is on standby with the Izanami until needed. They'll be dispatched to prosecute INEDAM warships as the second stage of our plan ramps up."
8557, "(fr)Chi"
8558, "(fr)Isfaril"
8559, "(fr)Jibril"
8560, "(fr)!html Our defenses should be sufficient to bog down IN.E.D.A.M.01's attack. When Bêta wing deactivates the carrier's heavy turrets and a fast attack is off the table, it will likely call in backup, leaving its forces temporarily off-balance. This gives us a brief window to clear a path from Amanu's fighterbay to IN.E.D.A.M.01's. Gunships and stealth controllers are our primary objective, but every drone killed tilts the balance in our favor. We don't know what forces INEDAM will call in or where they'll arrive, so we'll need to be quick on our feet. It may have its warships jump in a safe distance away from the fighting, or it may deploy them aggressively towards the station. Our science ships will broadcast subspace noise to disrupt INEDAM's arrival calculations as much as possible."
8561, "(fr)!html When the path has been cleared, we'll move into the third and final phase. Early in the INEDAM conflict, the GTA picked up a cache of Anubis fighters at the wreck of the <span class='green italic'>GTE Carter<$slashspan>. More recently, the Second Dawn Society lead an operation to steal a group of Carillon mines from an INEDAM salvage op. Our engineers have retrofitted several of these fighters as <span class='white'>fireships<$slashspan>. They've had their weapons, life support, and subspace drives removed and replaced with Carillon warheads and intelligence systems borrowed from Stiletto missiles. Using AI to fight AI has a nice sense of irony to it.

These fireships will use the callsign Sigma, and they'll set course for IN.E.D.A.M.01 as soon as they've launched. We've bolted on as much armor as we can, but without an onboard pilot, these ships will be extremely vulnerable. Alpha and Bêta will provide escort, while all other fighters will protect Amanu Station and the remaining capital ships."
8562, "(fr)Fireships"
8563, "(fr)!html From the Gallaecia op, we know that INEDAM ships use internal worker drones as damage control teams. Analysis of previous engagements with IN.E.D.A.M.01 suggest it can quickly repair battle damage when it needs to. As such, our objective is not to destroy the carrier, but to force it to retreat. To that end, Sigma will attempt to ram the enemy fighterbay. We believe a single fireship has sufficient yield to knock the bay out of commission, effectively crippling INEDAM's offensive capabilities. Alpha and Bêta, you'll want to pull away to avoid the blast.

At this point, all fighters will fall back to secure the station. With its railguns and drone bay offline, IN.E.D.A.M.01 will likely retreat, but it's proven hard to predict. Stick to the plan, knock out those guns, get the fireships in position, and keep your wits about you, and we'll get through this."
8564, "(fr)!html That's the plan for Amanu. Unfortunately, <span class='blue'>Habitat Bravo<$slashspan> still has been unable to get underway. The Elcano spaceframe predates the <span class='white'>Fourteen Years War<$slashspan> and has no tactical systems to speak of. In conjunction with the ship's large size and relatively thin plating, this means the habitat's best chance of survival is to avoid drawing attention. We've parked it 15 klicks away from the station with a small flotilla. After much deliberation, myself and the other commanders have decided <span class='white'>these are all the ships we can spare<$slashspan>. Bringing the habitat closer to Amanu would expose it to IN.E.D.A.M.01's main guns, and allocating more ships to its defense puts the 13,000 lives on this station at undue risk.

 I understand this is difficult. As soldiers, we've all sworn an oath to protect the civilians under our care. So have our Vasudan colleagues, and I've been told the SDS have their own equivalent. Unfortunately, the military realities of this situation have forced our hands. Do your jobs, and let the force at <span class='blue'>Bravo<$slashspan> do theirs."
8565, "(fr)!html We're heading into a complex situation with everything on the line. We've planned this operation to give us the best chance of survival, and we cannot spare pilots from any objective. Follow your orders to the letter, and be prepared to reorient when and if they change. Not to put too fine a point on it, we're asking you pilots, and our warship crews, to put your lives on the line more than you ever have before. I pray to whatever gods, saints, or ineffable cosmic forces may be out there that we don't lose a single life today, but the people in our care are counting on us. That's what we signed up for, and now more than ever, we have a responsibility, not only to the people on this station, but out there in the wider galaxy.

Get to your ships, everyone, and let's do Luyten proud."
8566, "(fr)!html We live to fight another day, pilots. Your defense of Amanu Station was nothing short of heroic, and our basic fighting ability remains intact. Combat engineers are cataloguing functional elements of the defense grid, SDS ships are lending their support to Amanu's infirmary, and HoL recon elements have joined what's left of the LNA sensor net to keep tabs on the INEDAM fleet. So far, they seem to be in full retreat.

With the INEDAM carrier's hangar offline, we've bought ourselves a reprieve, but given the self-repair capabilities the ship has demonstrated, a reprieve is the best we can hope for. INEDAM will not take this loss laying down, and we don't have any spare installations to flee to. Nevertheless, it will be some time before it can resume its offensive, and LNA plan to take the opportunity to replace their destroyed sensor buoys, so we should have advance warning. With that in mind, we should be mindful of the human element of our OrBat. You've fought a hard battle, pilots. Splice the mainbrace, hit the gym or the infirmary, catch up on sleep, or whatever else you need until ops resume tomorrow."
8567, "(fr)!html While your defense of Amanu Station was admirable, Allied casualties aboard the station and defending warships were high. Memorial services will be ongoing as we have capacity. On the other hand, the LNA's Elcano habitat survived the battle. Without immediate pressure, we believe the spaceframe can be made jump-capable before INEDAM resumes its attack. It is fortunate that we had enough warship assets to screen the both the habitat and Amanu, for which we much thank you as well."
8568, "(fr)!html While your defense of Amanu Station was admirable, Allied casualties were high. Losses among station and warship crew were significant, but little in comparison to the civilians aboard the Elcano habitat. We simply couldn't spare the assets to protect both the station and the habitat. We must turn the tide of this war before any more civilian lives are lost.

I would also like to remind you all that counseling services are still available, if you believe you need them."
8569, "(fr)There was nothing you could have done in this mission to save Habitat Bravo. The odds of its survival can be improved by protecting friendly warships throughout the campaign."
8570, "(fr)!html Station staff are working double-time to coordinate SAR and salvage ops. Once the immediate situation quiets down, our commanders are meeting to decide how to best capitalize on INEDAM's retreat. Expect news on that soon. You've won a hard-fought victory today. Prepare yourselves for whatever may come next, pilots. We'll need you at your best.

Dismissed!"
