9679, "(fr)Adhara Coalition"
9680, "(fr)Galactic Terran Intelligence"
9681, "(fr)The STX corporation dates back to 1976, where it operated heavy industry shipyards aimed at the exploitation of aquatic resources. Towards the end of the 21st century, the company partnered with the International Aeronautical and Space Administration to provide ocean-going launch platforms. When the economic uncertainty of the 2090s temporarily suspended IASA operations, STX leveraged its network of contacts to create its own spacecraft to take advantage of these platforms at a time when other manufacturers were cutting back on operations. Rebranded as STX Exploration, the company became the first Earth-based entity to mine the Asteroid Belt, competing directly with the Martian Han-Ronald Corporation.<br/><br/>STX Exploration is believed to have been a contributing factor in the severity of the 22nd century's Unification War. The demonstrated viability of Belt mining by a non-governmental entity lead to a boom in private spacecraft construction, as numerous companies on Earth and Mars shook off their economic stagnation to compete in the new market. When the discovery of the intersystem jump node to Delta Serpentis caused tensions between Earth, Mars, and the newly colonized Jupiter to boil over, more ships in Sol were operated by private parties than by any government, allowing corporate interests throughout the Belt and Jovian moon systems became minor belligerents in their own right and directly leading to the nascent GTA's struggle to centralize authority.<br/><br/>During the Fourteen Years War, the GTA contracted with STX Exploration to mine militarily valuable ores and develop a heavily armed freighter to safely move them. This influx of cash cemented STX's position as a heavyweight in galactic industry, and it maintains a near-monopoly over mining operations in the distant Laramis and Luyten systems."
9682, "(fr)Baranec Aquisitions"
9683, "(fr)Bessimer-Kohn"
9684, "(fr)Bessimer-Kohn began as a missile manufacturer, rising to prominence with the ubiquitous Hornet swarm missile. Since then, the company has established a reputation for innovation. Perhaps their biggest success is the Prometheus hull attack cannon, which put their experience with fire control sensors to a new use, using laser spectrometry to automatically adjust shot packaging for maximum effect."
9685, "(fr)Comet Propulsion Systems"
10710, "(fr)Dynamic Metamer"
9686, "(fr)Dynamic Metamer is a well-established company. The company was founded just over two decades before the outbreak of the Fourteen Years War, quite recently by the standards of space travel, but quickly developed a reputation for technical sophistication backed by robust engineering principles. With a mixed portfolio of civilian and military products, Dynamic Metamer seems well-positioned to remain a major player in the aerospace industry for years to come, although it is facing increasing competition from Nankam Aeronautical and Triton Dynamics."
644, "(fr)Han-Ronald Corporation"
9687, "(fr)The Han-Ronald Corporation can trace its lineage to a pre-Unification company from Sol. During the Unification War, the company built strikecraft for the Martian government. Han-Ronald floundered after Unification, finding their particular brand of technically sophisticated but expensive fighters lacking a market in the new peacetime environment. To reestablish themselves, Han-Ronald designed the Angel scout fighter as a loss leader, selling it at deeply discounted rates to the Alliance as a ship suitable for both peacetime customs enforcement and wartime escort duties. Han-Ronald hemorrhaged money on the Angel, but it served its purpose: other contractors looked for other niches, and when war broke out again, Han-Ronald was able to take a commanding presence in the market. Today, Han-Ronald continues to offer sophisticated fighters at cheap prices, but they now do so by taking advantage of lax regulations and tax loopholes in Regulus, Polaris, and Sirius, concerning many within the Alliance. It is hoped that newer fighters like Triton Dynamics' Ulysses will break up Han-Ronald's near monopoly going forward."
9688, "(fr)Johnson Munitions"
9689, "(fr)The old reliable workhorse of weapons contractors, Johnson Munitions is best known for their suite of fighter-scale primary cannons. Johnson's Avenger attack cannon was a critical development early in the Shivan Incursion, providing a means to pierce Shivan fighter shields without resorting to the unreliable MX-50 missile. Increased competition from Bessimer-Kohn, Triton Dynamics, and, surprisingly, Subach-Innes has seen the Avenger fall from its once-ubiquitous place, and Johnson has been gradually scaling up its engineering division to compensate."
9690, "(fr)Mesa Corporation"
9691, "(fr)The Mesa Corporation rose to prominence during the early days of Terran expansion, designing and manufacturing the security equipment needed by convoys in that turbulent time. Mesa's stock fell gradually from its heights as growing Allied authority decreased demand for their services, although the Fourteen Years War ensured they were never completely without a market. Mesa's combat designs have largely failed to keep up with the times, although the company has had some success transitioning into other verticals."
9692, "(fr)Nankam Aeronautical"
9693, "(fr)Nankam Aeronautical began as a manufacturer of scientific and exploratory equipment. Their early contracts were unfortunately riddled with some high-profile disasters, leaving Nankam with a tarnished reputation and inadequate cash flow. When the GTA admiralty put out a call for a strike cruiser that could answer the dreaded Vasudan Mekhet, Nankam took a chance and partnered with Snapka\Flegel Weapons Systems to create the GTC Fenris. The design was wildly creative, under budget, and met the Admiralty's needs exactly, so they in turn took a chance and overlooked Nankam's history. To call the result successful would be an understatement, and while Nankam is not a major player in the overall industry, they hold a dominating position within their niche."
10711, "(fr)RNI Systems"
9694, "(fr)RNI Systems is the Alliance's preferred contractor for projects requiring technical sophistication. While they're best known for the Faustus science cruiser, their portfolio also contains several high-end probes and various naval auxiliaries, along with various components of the Orion fleet carrier. RNI is also active in the civilian market, where they produce a modest range of space habitats. Internally, the company uses an internal organizational structure based on an engineering scrum team, which has given them a reputation for both creativity and unpredictability."
9695, "(fr)Subach-Innes"
9696, "(fr)Subach-Innes is a company with a long and successful history. They primarily act as a subcontractor, providing specialists to support other companies wherever their in-house expertise is lacking. Subach-Innes' attempts at building their own spacecraft have typically been met with trouble beyond their control, which is jokingly attributed to a 'curse'. They have had more success in weapons manufacturing, however."
645, "(fr)Triton Dynamics"
9697, "(fr)An up-and-coming company, Triton Dynamics was founded by ex-RNI luminary Alienor Miyamoto after she was ousted from her prior position. Triton leverages the same unorthodox organizational structure as RNI, but takes it a step further, actively recruiting those with nontraditional backgrounds and encouraging employees to try out different roles within the company. Triton worked closely with Vasudan teams to design the Ulysses fighter, and afterwards arranged an exchange program, making it one of the few truly mixed-species companies in Terran space. While Triton has a small portfolio and limited time to prove themselves, the Admiralty is keeping a close eye on them for future contracts."
9698, "(fr)Velocity: A Han-Ronald Company"
728, "(fr)Akheton Corporation"
9699, "(fr)The Akheton Corporation is a Vasudan aerospace manufacturer whose history is closely entwined with that of the Imperium itself. The discovery of interplanetary travel revolutionized Vasudan society, which had long been held back by its resource-poor homeworld. Initially, Akheton was just one of many companies competing in this new market. However, they were aware of research being done on the then-novel subspace domain which might allow for faster-than-light travel, and intentionally designed their ships with extension points so they could quickly be retooled if the technology paid off. When it did, Akheton assumed a dominant market position almost overnight, and were ultimately a key player in Vasudan unification. The modern Akheton Corporation retains its historical focus on innovation and forward thinking, and maintains a sprawling portfolio including high-performance strikecraft, science ships, and the mighty Typhon carriers. In a bit of historical irony, the one thing they've stopped building are cargo ships."
719, "(fr)Mekhu Enterprises"
9700, "(fr)Mekhu Enterprises is a Vasudan company of a largely civilian nature. They're best known for their low-cost, high-reliability freighters and transports, filling in the niche which the Akheton Corporation left behind. Mekhu does accept defense contracts, however, and during the Fourteen Years War, both sides of the company cooperated to create some truly fearsome cargo ships which could largely hold their own against Allied raids and are still relevant on modern battlefields."
732, "(fr)Sahr Corporation"
9701, "(fr)Sahr is a Vasudan company with a troubled history. They were once the Imperium's go-to warship contractor, and their tough, powerful cruisers shaped much of the early Fourteen Years War. Operating out of a sprawling shipyard complex in Altair, Sahr seemed like a rising star until the outbreak of the Hammer of Light rebellion. Many of Sahr's higher-level staff felt an affinity for the Hammer's religious ideology, and the Sahr Shipyards fell to HoL control almost without a fight. The company's Alpha Centauri branch continues to operate, but at a vastly reduced capacity."
9702, "(fr)Snapka\Flegel Weapons Systems"
9703, "(fr)Snapka\Flegel - the unusual punctuation is part of the company's legal name - largely produces unsophisticated but economical weapons for civilian security contractors, although a few of their missile offerings have found use among the GTA fighter corps. Snapka\Flegel had one breakout success in the design of the Fenris cruiser's main weapon: the launcher and magazines use the same space-efficient techniques Snapka developed for their fighter-scale missiles, giving the Fenris unusually good endurance for its size. Snapka's weapons have an unfortunate tendency of showing up in pirate hands, although this seems to have more to do with their ubiquity than any malfeasance on Snapka's part."
9704, "(fr)Agay Fluctuators"
9705, "(fr)Allender Hydraulic Actuators"
9706, "(fr)Capezzuto Textiles"
9707, "(fr)Enricco Ergonimic Systems"
646, "(fr)Gerace Corporation"
9708, "(fr)As aerospace firms go, the Gerace Corporation is rather unusual. Their portfolio is centered on three ships, the Proton, Electron, and Ion, all with wildly different roles and markets. It is unclear what Gerace's business strategy is, which has attracted some concern that the company may be a front$semicolon however, investigation into their accounts showed no evidence of this. While demand for the Ion has fallen nearly to zero, sales of Gerace's other two classes continue to keep the company solvent in spite of their odd approach to business."
9709, "(fr)Gulisano Precision Group"
9710, "(fr)The Gulisano Precision Group is virtually unknown to the public, but well-known to other industry professionals. Gulisano's main products are high-end construction equipment, which they lease to nearly every major shipwright in Allied space. They also build the Centaur support ships that keep Allied fighters armed and ready during extended engagements."
9711, "(fr)Holt Atmospheric Systems"
9712, "(fr)J Scott Weapons"
9713, "(fr)Named after its founder, Julianna 'Great' Scott, J Scott Weapons is a small firm specializing in high-performance missile weapons. Best known for their Phoenix line of long-ranged missiles, J Scott favors a quality over quantity approach, arguing that a standoff approach to combat pays for itself in the long run."
9714, "(fr)Kresge Connections"
9715, "(fr)The Regulus-based Kresge Connections is less of a manufacturer in their own right, and more of a broker, helping clients navigate the complex web of corporate relations surrounding Regulus. They do produce a small number of irregular weapons, however, such as EMP missiles and the Force-CXI tracking device, which are popular with special operations squadrons across the Alliance. Concerns about possible connections to the Regulus Syndicate must be approached carefully."
9716, "(fr)Kulas Management Group"
9717, "(fr)Pletcher Designs"
9718, "(fr)Wentz Acoustics"
9719, "(fr)Whiteside Construction"
9720, "(fr)Ever since the construction of Exarch Station in Delta Serpentis, Whiteside Construction has been the Alliance's go-to contractor for large-scale construction. With a portfolio including the Arcadia installation, the Orion carrier, and the Ganymede drydock, Whiteside combines generations of experience with project management with deep pools of their own engineering know-how. They also maintain a few designs of their own, most notably the eponymous Whiteside-class subspace survey ship."
647, "(fr)Northrop-Grumman"
9721, "(fr)Northrop-Grumman was founded on Earth before the advent of interplanetary travel, and was a major contractor for one of the Old Earth nation-states. As humanity moved upwards, so did Northrop, eventually providing some of the earliest space fighters to the United Nations and later United Earth militaries. During the Unification War, their Mustang line of fighters served as the bread and butter of Earth's fighter corps. Today, Northrop is a shell of its former self, with most of the company's assets being stranded in Sol, but the company continues to hang on, producing older-model fighters for private security firms."
9722, "(fr)Shandong Industrial"
9723, "(fr)Shandong Industrial is an older company most active in and around its headquarters in Antarès. The company is best known for its Syracuse orbital mining platforms, but they also produce other, more specialized stations and the Elepaio utility drone. For now, Shandong seems content to stick to its niche, giving the Alliance little reason to interact with it directly."
648, "(fr)Trenton Industries"
9724, "(fr)Trenton Industries got its start during the Unification War, where it unreservedly sold weapons to multiple mutually hostile factions. This reputation as an amoral arms dealer did not serve Trenton well in peacetime, however. Unable to secure any serious contracts, Trenton fired most of its original leadership and reinvented itself as a provider of exploration equipment, drawing on the same engineering expertise that had kept their combat spacecraft intact on the battlefield to instead keep colonists and explorers alive on the uncharted Frontière. This transition was surprisingly successful, and Trenton has become a well-regarded company in that space. To this day, they are reluctant to equip their ships with even basic point defense weaponry."
9725, "(fr)Andsager Logistics"
9726, "(fr)Andsager Logistics is a corporation with only two major products: the Bromios gas miner and the Marcellus refinery it partners with. There was a time when Andsager was the only name in gas exploitation, but the company's disinterest in innovating on its 'tried and true' designs lead to it gradually succumbing to brain drain, with most of engineers leaving for other companies and not being replaced. The sheer reliability of Andsager's products means it will hang on for quite some time, but the Alliance's official policy is to offer contracts elsewhere."
9727, "(fr)Ambrosia Logistical Solutions"
