1144, "(fr)A former GTA Marine, Kalev Ehin soured on the Alliance after the ill-fated Merneith boarding early in the Fourteen Years War. Since being discharged, Ehin returned to his home system of Antarès, where he became a vocal critic of the GTA, although not a very well-known one - until the publication of his book $quoteWar-Torn and Without Choice$quote. Ehin's harsh criticism was immediately popular with secessionist elements of Antarès' populace, although it was also faced with criticism over its political statements and factual inaccuracies. Nevertheless, Ehin was invited to Gulnara Local News, a radical program on the Gulnara HoloNet, as a political commentator. Ehin's rhetoric was a major factor in the rise of secessionist sentiment throughout Antarès, and his image has been used in anti-GTA protests in other systems as well. Any Allied officer interacting with Ehin is to answer his points calmly and with a minimum of confrontation so as to avoid giving him more ammunition for his screeds."
1142, "(fr)Admiral Po is an unconventional and somewhat controversial officer, but even his critics commend his dedication and loyalty to the GTA. Hailing from a middle-class family with no military background, Po defied expectations by graduating from the academy at the top of his class. His valedictorian speech centered on his upbringing on Beta Aquilae IV, the effects of crime and corruption on his friends and family, and his desire to help pave the way for a better future.<br/><br/>Admiral Po has high standards for his crew, his pilots, and himself. He's comfortable making snap decisions, and has repeatedly risked his flagship, the Intrépide, in key battles, jumping in to reinforce positions other admirals would have ceded. During the Fourteen Years War, Po developed a $quoteworthy opponent$quote reputation among Vasudan commanders$semicolon after the cease-fire, he was often appointed as the Alliance's representative in joint operations against the Shivans. Po's tendency for overwritten speeches and navel-gazing has been well-known since his academy days. Instead, he earns the trust of his subordinates by running a tight ship and fighting alongside them.<br/><br/>Po's tactics have drawn both praise and criticism, however, with detractors arguing that his affinity for risky moves could easily be exploited by a commander who understood his psychology. Some have even argued that his success should be attributed more to luck than skill. While Po's decision-making is unorthodox, he has been criticized for being too inflexible or $quoteby the book$quote in other matters, especially in his interactions with people outside his command. Allied Command's decision to send him to the troubled Antarès system, therefore, raised some eyebrows. The majority opinion is that Po's creativity and experience leading special forces make him uniquely qualified to untangle the crime rings that plague the decision, while a vocal minority lead by 10th Fleet's Admiral Shirazi argued that someone with a better diplomatic track record would be better equipped to understand Antarès' unique culture, social structure, and troubles."
1140, "(fr)The rogue Vasudan admiral styling himself Ozymandias seems to be a rising star in the Hammer of Light. Nothing is known about his personal life, and Vasudan Intelligence was unaware of him prior to his first appearance in Deneb. What is known is that Ozymandias is a skilled strategist well-versed in clever, deceitful maneuvers, and that he is fully committed to the Hammer's terrorist agenda. Ozymandias commands the Typhon-class destroyer Cardinal$semicolon sensor readings of this ship do not match any previously known Typhon, suggesting it may have been built by the Hammer rather than captured from the PVN. Ozymandias' aggressive strategy has been compared to that of the GTA's Admiral Po, with an emphasis on high-impact actions designed to leave his opponents off-guard. Following his entry into Antarès, Ozymandias focused his attacks on civilian population centers, Terran and Vasudan alike, in an attempt to force them onto the defensive."
9754, "(fr)Galactic Terran Intelligence began as a military intelligence service within the larger GTA League of Defense. Originally tasked with rooting out pirate and smuggler organizations, GTI expanded rapidly during the Fourteen Years War, eventually growing to encompass dedicated Intelligence, Special Operations, and Research &amp$semicolon Development departments, respectively under the GTD Soyakaze, Krios, and Repulse, with the GTD Legion providing overall organization and command.<br/><br/>The expansion of GTI's responsibilities was not matched by an expansion of oversight, a state of affairs which worsened with the loss of the GTD Legion to Shivan forces. After the destruction of the Lucifer, but before the Shivan Incursion was fully defeated, a long-concealed conspiracy within GTI tried to take advantage of the post-Sol chaos, commencing operations with the ultimate end of seizing control of the Alliance government by force. The conspiracy was headed by Admiral Marcus Glaive of the GTD Repulse and General Andreas Rybak of Internal Security, with extensive support within Research & Development and limited support within the other departments. R&amp$semicolonD's expertise with unconventional technologies was key to the insurrection. The rebellion's flagship, the Hades, was constructed in secret over many years, and upgraded with Shivan hybrid systems before its initial deployment$semicolon the insurrection is also called the Hades Rebellion as a result.<br/><br/>The Hades was eventually destroyed by a task force lead by the GTD Soyakaze during the Second Battle of Deneb, bringing the rebellion to an explosive end. The reintroduction of former GTI personnel proved to be a long and arduous process as the Alliance worked with the Department of Justice to ensure former rebels could not escape prosecution by feigning loyalty."
9753, "(fr)In the aftermath of Antarès' breakaway from the GTA, a coalition of scientific and industrial leaders, retired officers, and STX leadership, dissatisfied with Alliance policy but lacking a system to call their own, approached the General Assembly with a proposal. They asked that the Luyten system be granted autonomy in exchange for regular scientific contributions and cooperation on monitoring the Frontière for Shivan activity. This proposal was eventually accepted, and the Luyten New Alliance became an officially sanctioned client state. Officially, the relationship between the GTA and LNA is one of mutual assistance. The GTA provided capital to establish the LNA's habitats, and is obligated to provide military support should Luyten come under attack. Conversely, the LNA dedicates a portion of its research capacity to militarily relevant projects for the GTA navy.<br/><br/>The reality is more complicated. The Luyten New Alliance was born out of dissatisfaction, and the $quoteproposal$quote could more accurately be described as an ultimatum. There is still some ongoing tension between the two governments, especially from the LNA's fledgling military. These tensions are exacerbated by unverified but plausible reports of former GTI rebels now hiding among the LNA's research teams. Worse, empirical evidence suggests that there may have been some merit to the LNA's policy demands: their research output has significantly outperformed expectations, which observers in Luyten generally attribute to the LNA's political and regulatory restructuring. There is some concern that the LNA's success may attract talented researchers to emigrate from GTA space$semicolon proposals to import elements of LNA policy are being considered.<br/><br/>Tensions aside, the arrangement with the LNA has been highly successful overall. The latest generation of Naval jump drives and subspace sensors came out of Luyten, with civilian versions following shortly behind. The LNA's Tyr interceptor, Dainsleif flak platform, and experimental beam cannons have all attracted interest from naval procurement, and the design of Luyten's communication networks shows considerable promise as next-generation model for the GTA's core systems. While the relationship may have started with an ultimatum, it seems to have worked out for the best."
1132, "(fr)The Hammer of Light, also called the HoL or, disparagingly, Holly, represents the dark side of the Vasudan affinity for history. Citing esoteric prophecies of $quotegreat destroyers$quote which would wipe away the present world to make way for the next, a number of Vasudan naval personnel defected to the Shivan cause. While specific beliefs varied among sects, units, and individuals, at its core, Hammer of Light ideology equates the Shivans with these $quotedestroyers$quote, and asserts that assisting them is necessary for salvation in the next world. Throughout the Shivan Incursion, the Hammer of Light interfered with GTA and PVN operations, both through conventional military tactics and terrorist activity.<br/><br/>The destruction of the SD Lucifer shocked the Hammer of Light, with some leaders committing ritual suicide, but did not dissolve the organization as some had hoped. Instead, previously fringe sects came into power, bringing with them an ideological shift. The $quoteorthodox$quote view holds that the Shivans have merely withdrawn for a time$semicolon the Hammer, then, should prepare for their return. The $quoteimmanent$quote view, conversely, holds that the Shivan defeat represents a passing of the torch, and that the Hammer themselves now must $quoteembody the destroyers$quote. [The following is classified Level Rho.] Agents of Parliamentary Vasudan Intelligence embedded in the HoL are working to ferment distrust between these two sides, and to promote the $quoteorthodox$quote perspective so as to delay further terrorist activity.<br/><br/>The Hammer of Light's power base is significant. When the leaders of the Altair branch of the Vasudan Sahr Corporation defected, the Hammer of Light gained a sizeable fleet and a massive, well-defended shipyard to support it. They have captured many PVN warships, including multiple Typhon-class destroyers. Most concerning, however, are their retrofitted Imhotep science cruisers. These ships are concentrated around Vasudan worlds which suffered heavily during the previous years of war, and broadcast a message of joining a greater cause which has proven to be an effective recruiting tool.<br/><br/>The GTA and PVN continue to cooperate to bring an end to the HoL. Long-term plans for a joint endeavor have been in the works ever since the end of the Shivan Incursion. Ironically, by providing a common enemy to focus on, the Hammer of Light may have helped preserve the cease-fire between our civilizations."
1134, "(fr)The $quoteAntarès Federation$quote is a proposal for a populist, decentralized, independent government centered in the Antarès system. Taking inspiration from similar structures in Terran history, the Antarès Federation would treat each of its member worlds and habitats as equal partners, entitled to considerable autonomy$semicolon a central Parliamentary-style government would provide a framework for them to cooperate on the crime and social problems plaguing Antarès. Noted political theorist Diana Patil worked with the then-nascent Antarès Federation movement to draw up a proposed constitution, which includes a carefully chosen system of checks and balances to ensure no member, including the central authority, could come to wield too much power.<br/><br/>While the goals of the Antarès Federation movement are laudable, its means are less so. Proponents argue for total secession from the Galactic Terran Alliance, with no consideration to less dramatic reform, and have repeatedly asserted a readiness for armed uprising, should it become necessary. Worryingly, the Antarès militia and several of the larger private security companies are sympathetic to the Federal cause. A number of attacks against Alliance officials have been undertaken in the Federation's name, and while representatives of the movement have denied involvement, they have also refrained from condemning the attacks, calling them $quotea natural consequence of an intolerable system$quote.<br/><br/>The Antarès Federation moment has a complicated relationship with the broader Antarès for Antarians movement, or AfA. While the two groups have generally aligned goals, the AfA is far more willing to negotiate with the Alliance, and prefers a diplomatic resolution. As support for Federal ideas grows, proponents have been increasingly willing to distance themselves from the AfA, calling it weak and apologist. Notably, while the AfA movement counts many of Antarès' Vasudan population among its ranks, the AF movement is almost exclusively Terran.<br/><br/>Allied representatives in Antarès are to tread carefully around the Antarès Federation movement. Any actions which could be perceived as persecution could inflame the situation or drawing undecided Antarians to the movement. For the same reason, the Alliance is reluctant to outlaw the movement, at least until such a time as the anti-GTA violence can be positively traced to them."
9751, "(fr)Antarès Federation Movement"
9750, "(fr)Project INEDAM was a project of GTI Research and Development, an attempt to develop a fully autonomous strategic weapon in perhaps the most blatant violation of the Third Convention on Autonomous Weapons Systems imaginable. While 3CAWS does have limited exceptions for low-power defensive weapons, INEDAM was anything but. Its primary objective was to deploy forces into a system, seek and destroy Vasudan targets, and salvage the scrap as raw material for the construction of additional assets, eventually blockading all jump nodes out of the system and defeating the Vasudan fleet in detail, before moving on to the next Vasudan-held system. After the Shivan Incursion, INEDAM's focused changed to attacking Shivan targets, and eventually, to providing a 'legacy' should humanity fall, consuming the war debris to assemble a fleet powerful enough to take revenge. To this end, INEDAM was granted the most sophisticated neural network ever developed by Terran and Vasudan researchers, fabrication equipment to rival a Ganymede ring, and a complete dossier on all Terran, Vasudan, and Shivan vessels, armaments, and tactics. Primary construction was carried out at the Masada Redoubt in Antarès, with Vostok Station in Luyten handling the AI research. Both locations were chosen for secrecy.<br/><br/>The truth was more complicated, because there was a conspiracy going on within GTI. Many of the higher-ups believed that the Shivan defeat was merely a matter of time. Given the Shivan's initial push into Vasudan-held space, they may have hoped the PVN and the Shivan Armada would exhaust each other, leaving the GTA unopposed. Much of Project INEDAM's funding was quietly funneled to rebel projects, most notably the Hades carrier, even as arguments about what INEDAM's true purpose should be turned violent.<br/><br/>Some time after the defeat of the GTI rebellion, INEDAM's construction module reached Luyten and united with the AI controller. Erroneously interpreting GTI's defeat as human extinction, it began its mission, attacking targets of opportunity - primarily STX Exploration cargo depots and mining ships - to build up a supply of raw material. It quickly established a diverse array of drones, ranging from efficient disposable swarm combatants to highly advanced stealth fighters and EWAR ships, sufficient to challenge the GTA, PVN, and LNA forces arranged against them."
9749, "(fr)A convergence engine is an obsolete precursor to a jump drive, popular in Sol shortly before the outbreak of the Unification War. Like a jump drive, a convergence engine allows for faster-than-light travel, although its manner of operation is entirely different. Where a jump drive opens a discrete subspace tunnel for the ship to travel down, a convergence engine temporarily dissolves the subspace barrier, causing the ship to enter a strange state where it is governed by subspace physics while partially existing in realspace as well. While this state is of considerable scientific interest, it has extremely limited practical applications for the simple reason that the engine must remain active during the entire jump, dramatically increasing power requirements over distance. (An uncontrolled shutdown of a convergence engine has been described as by one researcher as $quotea highly efficient way to convert a ship and crew to exciting new forms of physics$quote.) A convergence engine can be more efficient than a jump drive over very short distances, but given the safety risks, the cost of installing and maintaining two separate FTL systems, and the very modest gains offered even in the ideal circumstances, convergence engines have been largely relegated to a research tool and occasional holonovel special effect."
9748, "(fr)Convergence Engine"
1138, "(fr)The existence of subspace was first suggested in the mid-21st century to account for surprising experimental results by the Ataraxis I and II deep-space probes. By the end of the century, the fringe theory had become accepted science with proven applications in transportation, communication, and power generation, although the last only on extremely small scales. By far the most well-known application of subspace is as the medium of travel for jump drives.<br/><br/>Two types of subspace jumps are possible. The more common type are intrasystem jumps, which create a temporary tunnel through subspace between two points within a system. Intrasystem jumps are affected by both distance and gravity, so getting to a specific destination may require jumping to one or more intermediate locations. These navigational adjustment points are a common site of pirate activity, and both governmental and private security forces spend considerable time and effort protecting them.<br/><br/>Jumps between systems are different. Generating a subspace tunnel without the assistance of a star's gravity is beyond current science, so ships must make use of naturally occurring intersystem jump nodes. The process is fundamentally the same$semicolon however, the drive must be specifically reinforced, or resonance from the jump node will tear it apart. This is standard practice on ships of transport scale and above. Until the Shivan Incursion, however, miniaturizing this technology to fighter scale was prohibitively expensive$semicolon it was typically reserved for special operations squadrons, although ships on intelligence-gathering missions sometimes had their escape pods fitted with them as well. Collaboration with Vasudan teams has reduced the cost of small-scale intersystem drives, and they are becoming standard equipment for Alliance fighters and bombers.<br/><br/>Intersystem jump nodes vary considerably in stability and throughput. Most nodes exhibit some form of instability. This typically manifests as $quoteshifting$quote, where the jump node moves intermittently to a new position in the system, and $quotephasing$quote, where the node becomes inaccessible for a time but later return. These forms of instability are considered acceptable, and are relatively well understood. A much more serious problem comes in form of node collapse. While theoretically possible, this phenomenon has never been observed to happen naturally$semicolon however, node collapse was accidentally induced during the destruction of the SD Lucifer during its jump to Sol, severing the system from the rest of the galaxy.<br/><br/>Subspace has several unusual tactical implications. There are many possible subspace paths between any two points in space, and specialized equipment is needed to accurately track a vessel. Subspace ambushes, while technically possible, are very rare due to the need to cover all possible paths, although specialized jump drives which can quickly move through the subspace barrier have been proposed. Shield systems - both the Shivan originals nor our reproductions - do not function in subspace, which was a key factor in the destruction of the Shivan Lucifer."
1136, "(fr)The species designated $quoteShivans$quote appeared without warning in 2335, attacking both Terran and Vasudan forces with a ferocity that brought a quick end to the Fourteen Years War. On every level, very little is known about the Shivans$semicolon even their name is a provisional designation, referring to a destroyer deity in Earth's Hindu religion. Shivan ships do not mount gravity generators, and Shivan organisms are well-adapted to maneuvering in zero-G, suggesting that they do not originate in a terrestrial environment. Further complicating matters are the apparently synthetic components integrated into Shivan physiology, most notably a plasma-based defensive weapon. Shivan cybernetics is bidirectional, with Shivan technology containing organic components, although the operating principles are still similar enough to be understood. The shield systems used by Terran and Vasudan fighters, for example, are derived from captured Shivan equipment.<br/><br/>Xenobiologists know very little about Shivan society. A leading hypothesis is the hive mind theory, arguing that Shivan society is broken down in specialized functions driven by a collective intelligence. The most convincing evidence supporting this theory is the behavior of Shivan forces following the destruction of the Lucifer, the turning point of the Shivan Incursion. Other experts caution against attributing insectoid properties to the Shivans, regardless of their appearance and behavior. Shivan communication seems to occur in the electromagnetic spectrum, though efforts to decode their transmissions have yielded no meaningful results to date.<br/><br/>Alien artifacts discovered on Altair IV suggest that neither Terran nor Vasudan society were the first victims of Shivan aggression. A species designated the $quoteAncients$quote were attacked by a Shivan fleet and unable to repel it, largely owing to their inability to pierce Shivan shield systems. It is unknown how old the Shivans truly are, nor how many civilizations they have destroyed."
1135, "(fr)Shivans"
1131, "(fr)The Vasudan species hails from the Bêta Hydri system, now called Vasuda in their honor. They evolved on the fourth planet in the system, known as Vasuda Prime. The planet is at the inner end of the star's habitable zone, rendering it hot, arid, and hostile. Vasudan physiology evolved down radically different lines than our own, with knockoff effects on their history, culture, and psychology. Vasuda Prime's inhospitality could have lead to intense competition. Instead, the Vasudan people developed a complex network of social connections and trade relations, helping make the most of the planet's resources. With the invention of space flight and the discovery of rich resource deposits deeper in the system, Vasudan society soon formally united under what Terrans would call a parliamentary government to ensure equitable access to this new wealth.<br/><br/>Terran society struggles to understand Vasudans overall. The concept of a unilateral central government making decisions about resource allocation, coupled with the relative homogeneity of Vasudan culture, evokes Terran dystopic fiction. The Vasudan emphasis on history and mysticism is often seen as backwards, or at least strange. Misunderstandings such as these compromised early diplomatic efforts, prolonging the Fourteen Years War by at least a decade. In all interactions with Vasudan people, it is crucial to remember that they are a distinct species, and their culture is adapted to their needs, not ours.<br/><br/>Vasudan society has a complex hierarchy, which was at first misidentified as a caste system. It is now understood that this hierarchy comes with a high degree of social mobility, and was intentionally designed to promote extreme meritocracy. This system is supported by a complex system of honorifics baked into the Vasudan language at a low level. This language, too, was intentionally created, combining elements of many historical languages into one, in a way that makes intuitive sense to native speakers. Some Vasudans intentionally use language in a way that emphasizes features from their individual ethnic backgrounds, while others make a point of favoring as wide an assortment as possible$semicolon this is, apparently, something of a sensitive issue. One particular area of confusion concerns gender markers. As an adaptation to their arid environment, Vasudans, like most fauna from their world, are sequentially hermaphroditic, and most spend most of their time as $quotemale$quote, undergoing a temporary transition for reproductive purposes. Until both species understand each other more closely, gender will be one of the many sources of mistranslation.<br/><br/>As the only extant sapient extraterrestrial species in known space, the Vasudan species is of intense interest to Terran xenobiologists. That they would have evolved on such a hostile world, while much more hospitable planets have produced nothing more complex than non-sapient xenofauna. Most mainstream Vasudan mystical traditions assert the existence of $quotegods from the stars$quote which assisted the Vasudan people in their infancy, and while these myths sound implausible by Terran standards, the discovery of alien ruins in the nearby Altair system has lead some credibility to this theory. Cross-referencing the myths with known historical events suggests this visit would have taken place roughly eight thousand years ago, the same time that the $quoteAncient$quote civilization was losing its own conflict with the Shivans. The significance of this, if any, is a subject of fervent speculation, but so far, no hard answers have emerged.<br/><br/>Owing to Vasuda Prime's desert conditions and the incompatibility of spoken Vasudan with Terran physiology, Vasudan ships are typically assigned reporting names drawn from Egyptian mythology. Considering the Egyptian Empire's strength and long history, many Vasudans find the comparison flattering, and some even take $quoteTerran names$quote from the same sources."
9746, "(fr)Terrans"
9747, "(fr)[This is a translation of an article intended for Vasudan observers. A copy of the original may be requested from any terminal.]<br/><br/>Humanity evolved as an apex predator species on Earth, the third planet in the Sol system. With some technological assistance, these ancient humans were able to establish societies on each of Earth's major land masses, aside from a frigid polar continent which still held temporary research settlements. Modern humans continue to leverage this adaptability, spreading to every planet in their space with an appropriate atmosphere in spite of a cultural wariness of genetic modification$semicolon however, some simple modifications to increase life span and remove common medical problems have become common.<br/><br/>Human civilization developed basic spaceflight long before global unity. While some scientific missions were conducted jointly under the International (later Interplanetary) Aeronautical and Space Administration, many human nation-states also maintained their own space programs, especially for missions with an economic objective. It should not be surprising, then, that this phase of human history was rife with conflict, both political and piratical.<br/><br/>The development of the Galactic Terran Alliance, and the use of the term $quoteTerran$quote itself, is a rejection of humanity's fractious past. Humanity is as culturally and ideologically diverse as ever$semicolon everything from religion and culture to the proper role of technology and the military is a possible ground for debate. In the ashes of the Unification War, humanity came together to form a new alliance, one in which this diversity would be embraced as a strength, and where disputes would be resolved with words, not weapons."
9759, "(fr)Known Species"
9752, "(fr)The Antarès Federation is a populist, decentralized, independent government centered in the Antarès system. Taking inspiration from similar structures in Terran history, the constitution of the Antarès Federation describes each of its member worlds and habitats as equal partners under a central Parliamentary-style government, supported by a carefully chosen system of checks and balances designed with the help of noted political theorist Diana Patil$semicolon in spite of this, the new government's first act was a vote to grant itself emergency powers, which passed unanimously.<br/>The movement that would become the Antarès Federation had been a thorn in the Alliance's side throughout its attempt to restore law and order in Antarès. The influence of secessionist media figures, most notoriously the firebrand Kalev Ehin, brought popular approval of the Alliance to historic lows, mirrored by a growing prevalence of Federal ideas. A major turning point came on November 19, 2336, with the Battle of Camp Angel. Alliance forces reinforced the refugee camp in expectation of a Hammer of Light raid, which was successfully repulsed$semicolon pro-secession pundits, however, spun the battle as the Alliance using refuges to achieve their military objectives. Camp Angel's largely Vasudan population proved unfortunate as well, with the battle giving the Federation an effective talking point to appeal to Antarès' Vasudan diaspora. Shortly thereafter, open violence between the Federation and the Alliance became common, culminating in the Allied fleet's withdrawal from the system.<br/>Besides Antarès itself, the Federation lays claim to Bêta Cygni, Betelgeuse, Ikeya, and Ribos, to which it holds the only jump nodes. In spite of its promises to focus on the problems plaguing Antarès, early Federal activity focused primarily on reinforcing their borders and spinning up industry to augment their fleet of stolen GTA craft and retrofitted cargo ships. The Federation maintains limited trade with the Alliance, but is more willing to deal with the Vasudan Empire. While the government maintains considerable popular support, these policies have been seen as unsustainable, both economically and politically. As Antarian political commentator Ian Bonnay put it, $quoteThe Antarès Federation did the impossible, both in defeating a much stronger power militarily, and in building a shared identity across the system. Ask the average person on the street, and they will identify themselves as Antarian before species, ethnicity, or political orientation. This is one perspective. Another is that the Federation rose to power through hatred, violence, and terror. Both are true. For the Federation to set policy which makes reparations for the evils it carried out, no matter how necessary, must therefore be seen as nothing less than a moral imperative.$quote"
