10673, "(fr)Vasudan Mine Missile Weak"
2136, "(fr)Une Carrote"
2184, "(fr)Howell"
2221, "(fr)GTM-205 Howell Torpedo"
2224, "(fr)During the Great War, nowhere was the superiority of Shivan warships clearer than the comparison against their Terran and Vasudan counterparts. While the dreaded Lucifer, with its impenetrable shielding and planet-killing beam weapons, was emblematic of the Shivan fleet, even the relatively common Demon-class destroyer proved itself more than a match for the Terran Orion and Vasudan Typhon. While frontline warships like the Galatea held back the incursion, a crash refit program was instituted on others, augmenting their armaments with experimental torpedoes produced by GTI Research and Development. For better or for worse, these weapons were never tested, as the destruction of the Lucifer brought the war to an end. GTI issued a recall order for these torpedoes, citing flaws in their targeting systems and a concerning tendency for unsuccessful launches. It is now understood that GTI massively over-represented the significance of these flaws, and used the recall to route funding to their rebellion.<br/><br/>Plans for these torpedoes were discovered by post-rebellion investigations. One design, the GTM-205 Howell, was selected for mass production, and has become standard armament on the Orion-class destroyer. Orions have returned to their original place as central fleet elements, not only providing strategic coordination and strikecraft support, but directly attacking enemy positions alongside the rest of their battlegroups.<br/><br/>The Howell is a massive weapon, and no bomber, not even the GTB Ursa, can carry a single one. In spite of this, their actual firepower is only moderate, comparable to the Tsunami. Much of the Howell's mass is dedicated to thruster systems, allowing it to track targets at extreme range. The Howell is protected by experimental collapsed-core molybdenum armor, coupled with a sophisticated RCS suite to evade counterfire. The Howell is both the fastest and most durable bomb produced by Terran science, and virtually immune to interception.<br/><br/>The Howell's main drawback is its high cost. Howells have been decried as emblematic of the military-industrial complex. Critics of the Alliance often point to funding going to weapons manufacturers in Delta Serpentis and Beta Aquilae rather than troubled systems like Antarès and Sirius, and the Howell is perhaps the most commonly cited example. Rumors abound that Alliance investigators did not properly handle the Howell's stated flaws, leading to calls for independent audits. Allied officers are reminded not to lend credence to such rumors."
2271, "(fr)Aratrum"
2315, "(fr)PVM-300 Aratrum Torpedo"
2316, "(fr)The PVM-300 Aratrum is the first torpedo designed by Vasudans as a true anti-capital ship weapon. During the Fourteen Years War, Imperial analysts believed that the then-revolutionary PVD Typhon would bring the war to a short conclusion. In support of this, Parliament quickly announced that a 'destroyer killer' would be added to the Typhon's already deadly arsenal. Had the Aratrum been deployed as intended, it would likely have spelled to a quick Imperial victory over the Alliance. In a shocking turn of events, a group of Vasudan dissidents contacted the Alliance with the intent to warn them of this new threat, and worked with their Terran handlers to delay development on the Aratrum as long as possible$semicolon as a result, much like the Howell, the Aratrum wasn't deployed until near the end of the Shivan Incursion, and then only on rear-line units that saw little action.<br/><br/>The strengths and weaknesses of the Aratrum remain classified, so no comparisons between the Howell and the Aratrum torpedoes have yet been made. Contradicting statements by the PVN and the PVE cause further challenges in determining the role of the weapon. Whereas PVN admirals boast the superiority of the weapon over the GTA's, PVE officials downplay it as a defensive weapon. What we have been told is that the Aratrum carries multi-yield warheads, and its official test-flight revealed that it is capable of aspect lock. Like the Howell, the Aratrum has powerful thrusters and is hard to intercept$semicolon also like the Howell, its large size makes it incompatible with all extant bombers. The PVN's unwillingness to disclose details about the Aratrum is especially frustrating in light of the defection of some of the original engineers to the Hammer of Light."
