3224, "(fr)An electronic countermeasure (ECM) is a device designed to trick or deceive radar, sonar or other detection systems. It may be used both offensively and defensively to deny targeting information to an enemy. The system may make many separate targets appear to the enemy, or make the real target appear to disappear or move about randomly. Most forces use ECM to protect their craft from attack during stealth or surprise operations. It is frequently coupled with stealth advances so that the ECM systems have an easier job. Offensive ECM often takes the form of jamming while defensive ECM usually comes in the form of blip enhancement or distortion."
3360, "(fr)Cluster Baby"
3375, "(fr)Cluster Bomb Baby"
3578, "(fr)AN/ALE-650"
10688, "(fr)AN/ALE-650 'Type One'"
10689, "(fr)The AN/ALE-650 is an EWAR ordnance fitted inside standard GTA flare launchers. Like most countermeasures, the Type One works by emitting regular IFF and radio pulses to spoof the signature of the host ship from enemy missile lock. The AN/ALE-650's electronics are tuned for high intensity, and compensate for short range and battery life with a very high spoofing factor. It is most effective when deployed just before a missile enters its terminal approach phase.<br/><br/>The 650 was originally intended as part of a suite of countermeasures. While the other variants were cancelled during OpEval, the 650 is often called the $quoteType One$quote owing to the awkwardness of its official designation."
10690, "(fr)DIRCM BriteBurst"
10691, "(fr)The DIRCM BriteBurst is a cost-effective but unsophisticated countermeasure rarely encountered in the GTA but common in the civilian world. Unlike the sophisticated electronics of other modern countermeasures, the BriteBurst employs extreme heat to break missile lock. While of limited effect against aspect-seeking missiles, these countermeasures are highly effective against the heat-seeking ordnance typically employed by, and against, private security forces.<br/><br/>LOCAL ADDENDUM: Post-flight review of guncam footage collected during the Carter engagement indicates that the BriteBurst is unusually effective against INEDAM's shield-breaker missiles. Our working theory is that the BriteBurst's long active phase interacts favorably with the shield-breaker's long flight time. Because of this the flare should be launched early while the missile is still in cruising flight. Security contractor Makarov has made his wing's supply of BriteBurst's available to any pilot wishing to use them."
10692, "(fr)RIVCM-650"
10693, "(fr)The RIVCM-650, short for 'Radio Interference Vasudan CM-650', is the GTA designation for a reverse engineering of the AN/ALE-650 fielded by PVN forces during the Terran-Vasudan War. It works on the exact same principle: emitting regular IFF and radio pulses to spoof the signature of the host ship from enemy missile lock. Early in the war, Terran fighters relied on their countermeasures to compensate for their larger relative size and lower maneuverability. Fortuitously for Vasudan engineers, acquisition of the 'Type One' was extremely easy, as most engagement sites were often littered with dozens of them afterword. Integration of countermeasure technology into the PVN fighter corps was soon followed by heavier fighter designs. Today, the RIVCM-650 is standard issue for all Vasudan strikecraft."
